2025-12-11 00:00:00.881 | WARNING  | agentscope.message.msg:__init__:145 - A new field `role` is newly added to the message. Please specify the role of the message. Currently we use a default "assistant" value.Scientist0: Thought: The existing literature highlights a growing interest in combining game-theoretic models with machine learning to improve predictive accuracy and interpretability in auction settings. Paper 1 demonstrates the value of integrating product embeddings and game-theoretic priors via a multi-branch mixture density network (MDN), but it treats game-theoretic predictions as static inputs rather than dynamically updated beliefs. Paper 2 explores equilibrium learning through multiagent dynamics, suggesting that strategic behavior can be learned end-to-end, while Paper 3 reveals deep structural insights—such as virtual welfare maximization—that govern optimal dynamic auctions. However, none of these works explicitly model how *uncertainty* in both strategic behavior and item characteristics jointly shapes auction duration distributions.

My key insight is that auction durations are not just functions of fixed features or equilibria, but emerge from the *interaction between evolving bidder beliefs* (informed by game theory) and *semantic properties of items* (captured via embeddings). Moreover, most prior work assumes stationarity in bidder strategies, which fails in dynamic markets where participants adapt over time. To address this, I propose enhancing the multi-branch MDN framework by introducing **game-theoretic inductive biases as learnable, differentiable modules**—not just as input features—thereby enabling the network to refine theoretical predictions using data-driven feedback. This creates a hybrid architecture where the model learns *when and how much to trust* game-theoretic assumptions based on observed deviations in real bidding behavior.

